Many women who wish to divorce their abusive husbands are unable to do so because of the social stigma involved, forcing them to remain in invariably abusive situations for life. Both the Indian government and the Syrian government face continual criticism from ethnocentric advocates seeking to enact policies of racial or religious purity in the respective countries, the primary arguments being founded in culture.

The idea of protecting innocent citizens from foreign influences and of preserving native culture has been a long-standing argument in both the Kashmiri and the Syrian contexts, drawing upon an assumption that only a protected cultural identity maintains strength during times of foreign influence.

I am an unbiased outsider, therefore, I must tell you that when it
comes to women's rights, you are potentially very, very wrong. There
would be very few women who would prefer to live a half literate
backwards life in the south of India with the blocks permanently set
on rudeness than be thriving and assured in the urban, culturally-free
cities of Iran...
